    <body>
        <section id="intro">
            <h1>No.</h1>
        </section>

        <section id="stats">
            <ul>
                <li><a href="http://www.gallup.com/poll/148427/say-bible-literally.aspx">30%</a> of Americans believe the Earth is around 6000 years old.</li>
                <li><a href="http://www.gallup.com/poll/155003/hold-creationist-view-human-origins.aspx">46%</a> of Americans believe that humans were created in their present form within the last 10,000 years.</li>
                <li>In truth, the Earth is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Age_of_the_Earth"> 4.54 billion</a> years old. The universe is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Age_of_the_universe">13.8 billion</a> years old. </li>
                <li>We know this because... <a href="https://xkcd.com/482/">science</a>. </li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="summary">
            <p>
                The United States owes much of its prosperity and status in the world to the advancement of science and technology. 
                Generations of immigrants have been attracted to our shores because of the free exchange of ideas grounded in the scientific method. 
                In {{year}} we are witnessing a waning respect for the importance of science. 
                Whether it's the sizable population who denies evolution, refuse vaccinations or deny climate change, a small but vocal population ignore the facts and instead rely on [[[[[[[]]]]]]] 
            </p>
            <p>
                Science literacy is not a luxery, it's essential for economic growth and further understanding of our universe and ourselves.                
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="quotes">
            <p id="nye">
                <i class="fa fa-2x fa-quote-left"></i> And I say to the grownups, if you want to deny evolution and live in your world, in your world that's completely inconsistent with everything we observe in the universe, that's fine. But don't make your kids do it because we need them. We need scientifically literate voters and taxpayers for the future. We need people that can — we need engineers that can build stuff, solve problems." <br />
                — <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gHbYJfwFgOU&feature=share&list=PLE50FC91A844EEC33&index=73">Bill Nye</a>, Science Guy
            </p>

            <p id="tyson">
                <i class="fa fa-2x fa-quote-left"></i> The good thing about Science is that it's true whether or not you believe in it." <br/>
                — <a href="https://twitter.com/neiltyson/status/345551599382446081">Neil deGrasse Tyson</a>, Astrophysicist, Director of the Hayden Planetarium, Host of Cosmos
            </p>
